      "id": "96f9f25e64ed6607",
      "text": "We are wired for learning in motion.  When learning experiences are linked to movement, music and pattern, that experience is deeply embedded in our bodies, embodied in all aspects of our nervous system- from the nerves that fire the muscles to the regions of the brain that activate those nerves, or map that [[Lived Experience]] to multiple regions of our brain.  This is captured in the film Akela and the Bee, and in Aristotle's peripatetic approach to teaching and learning."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "76b8eb78a8c45db8",
      "text": ">\"Are you someone who likes to think on your feet? If so, you've got something in common with the followers of the ancient Greek philosopher Aristotle. Not only a thinker and teacher, Aristotle was also a walker, and his students were required to walk along beside him as he lectured while pacing to and fro. Thus it was that the Greek word peripatētikos (from peripatein, meaning \"to walk up and down\") came to be associated with Aristotle and his followers. By the way, the covered walk in the Lyceum where Aristotle taught was known as the \"peripatos\" (which can either refer to the act of walking or a place for walking).\"\n>\n[https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/peripatetic Merriam Webster]"
